This example, will create a WebSocket connection to a server at wss://example.com/push. When the connection is opened, the client sends a message to the server indicating that it wants to subscribe to the notifications topic. When the server has a new notification to push to subscribed clients, it sends a message to the client with a type of notification and a payload containing the notification data. The client then handles the received notification by calling a handleNotification function which logs the notification to the console. In a real-world application, the handleNotification function would likely perform more meaningful actions, such as displaying the notification to the user.


// Create a WebSocket connection
const socket = new WebSocket('wss://example.com/push');

// When the socket is opened, send a message to the server to subscribe to a specific topic
socket.addEventListener('open', (event) => {
  socket.send(JSON.stringify({ topic: 'notifications' }));
});

// When a message is received from the server, handle it accordingly
socket.addEventListener('message', (event) => {
  const message = JSON.parse(event.data);
  switch (message.type) {
    case 'notification':
      handleNotification(message.payload);
      break;
    default:
      console.log(`Received unknown message type: ${message.type}`);
  }
});

// Handle a received notification
function handleNotification(payload) {
  console.log(`Received notification: ${payload}`);
  // Do something with the notification, such as displaying it to the user
}

